{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}} {{BLP sources|date=October 2011}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Christopher Franke | image = | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_name = Christoph Franke<ref name=Poland1984>{{cite AV media notes | title=Poland | others=Tangerine Dream | year=1984 | type = [http://cdn.discogs.com/9T0vqPgZLo2cHWszgQhQy1tntj4=/fit-in/600x600/filters:strip_icc():format(jpeg):mode_rgb():quality(96)/discogs-images/R-263442-1309543213.jpeg.jpg inner sleeve of record two] | publisher = Jive Electro | id = HIP 22 | url = {{Discogs release|263442|type=album|pure_url=yes}}}}</ref> | alias = Chris Franke | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|4|6}} | death_date = | origin = [[Berlin]], Germany | instrument = [[Drum set|Drums]], keyboards, synthesizers | genre = {{hlist|[[New age music|New age]]|[[Psychedelic music|psychedelia]]|[[electronica]]}} | occupation = Musician, songwriter | years_active = | label = | associated_acts = [[Tangerine Dream]], [[Agitation Free]] | website = {{URL|christopherfranke.com/}} | current_members = | past_members = }} '''Christopher Franke''' (born 6 April 1953, [[Berlin]]) is a German musician and composer. From 1971 to 1987 he was a member of the electronic group [[Tangerine Dream]]. Initially a drummer with The Agitation, later renamed [[Agitation Free]], his primary focus eventually shifted to keyboards and synthesizers as the group moved away from its [[psychedelic rock]] origins. While he was not the first musician to use an [[analog sequencer]], he was probably the first to turn it into a live performance instrument, thus laying the rhythmic foundation for classic [[Tangerine Dream]] pieces and indeed for the whole [[Berlin School of electronic music|Berlin school]] sound.
After his departure from the group, he founded the [[Sonic Images]] record label, a [[new-age music]] label called [[Earthtone]] and the [[Berlin Symphonic Film Orchestra]], and produced a number of solo music works. After leaving Tangerine Dream, his only live concert was on 9 October 1991 at the Astoria Theatre in London. He performed on stage with [http://DingDingMusic.com Edgar Rothermich] (a.k.a. Richard E. Roth) who is also his producer and engineer on all his solo projects and film music after 1990.
Franke moved to Los Angeles in 1991 to pursue film work. In 1995 he scored the [[AFI Conservatory|AFI]] short ''[[Requiem (1995 film)|Requiem]]''. He may be best known for composing the music for the science fiction television series ''[[Babylon 5]]'', as well as the score of the [[anime]] movie ''[[Tenchi Muyo! in Love]]'' and in 2005 the music for German musical ''[[Ludwig²]]'' (with [[Konstantin Wecker]]).
