{{other uses2|Thamrin}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Mohammad Husni Thamrin | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = Portrait of Mohammad Husni Thamrin | birth_name = | birth_date = 16 February 1894 | birth_place = [[Sawah Besar|Weltevreden]], [[Jakarta|Batavia]], [[Dutch East Indies]] | death_date = {{BirthDeathAge|df=yes| |1894|02|16|1941|01|11|yes}} | death_place = [[Senen]], Batavia, Dutch East Indies | death_cause = | resting_place = [[Karet Bivak Cemetery]], Jakarta | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | nationality = Indonesian | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | occupation = Politician | years_active = 1919–1940 | religion = | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = [[List of National Heroes of Indonesia|National Hero of Indonesia]] }} '''Mohammad Husni Thamrin''' (16 February 1894&nbsp;– 11 January 1941) was an Indonesian political thinker and [[National Hero of Indonesia|National Hero]].
==Biography== Thamrin was born in [[Sawah Besar|Weltevreden]], [[Jakarta|Batavia]] (modern day Jakarta), [[Dutch East Indies]], on 16 February 1894.{{sfn|Soedarmanto|2007|p=14}} His father, Thamrin Mohd. Tabri, was the son of an English businessman who owned hotel Ort in Batavia, but had been raised by his Javanese uncle and had adopted his name. Thamrin was therefore born into a neo-[[priyayi]] class and in 1906, his father became district head ({{lang|id|wedana}}) under Governor General [[Johan Cornelis van der Wijck]].<ref>B.O.B. Hering, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20072069?seq=1 M.H. Thamrin and his Quest for Indonesian Nationhood], 1917-1941, Stein (Limburg), 1996</ref> After graduating from Koning Willem III Gymnasium,{{sfn|Soedarmanto|2007|p=14}} Thamrin took several government jobs before working for the shipping company [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]].{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}}
In 1919, Thamrin was elected a member of the Jakarta City Council. He later became deputy mayor. In 1927 he was elected to the [[Volksraad (Dutch East Indies)|Volksraad]]; he soon formed the National Fraction ({{lang|id|Fraksi Nasional}}) to unite ten groups of [[Indonesian National Awakening|Indonesian nationalists]] under one flag{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} and counteract the reactionary Fatherlands Club ({{lang|nl|Vaderlandsche Club}}). Along with [[Soetomo|Dr. Soetomo]], Parindra's chair, Thamrin believed that independence could be achieved through cooperation with the Dutch colonial government.{{sfn|Elson|2008|p=60}}
As a Volksraad member, Thamrin and Kusumom Utoyo went to eastern [[Sumatra]] to look into working conditions at plantations there. Disgusted by what they found, upon his return Thamrin gave a speech condemning the plantation owners.{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} He criticised the legalised gambling and corporal punishments given for minor offences.{{sfn|Soedarmanto|2007|p=13}} In 1935 he was a founding member of the Grand Indonesia Party ({{lang|id|Partai Indonesia Raya}}, or Parindra).{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}}
After the death of Dr. Soetomo in 1938, Thamrin became deputy chair of Parindra. In at a meeting of the Volksraad in 1939, Thamrin proposed that the Dutch terms Nederlands Indie, Nederlands Indisch and Inlander (Dutch Indies, Dutch Indian, and Dutch Indians) be replaced with the nationalist terms Indonesia, Indonesisch, and Indonesier (Indonesia, Indonesian, and Indonesians). Although this received majority support in the Volksraad, the Dutch government vetoed the motion. After his request, the colonial government kept him under surveillance.{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} By 1940, his proposal for the use of the term Indonesian had begun to receive consideration, much to Thamrin's perplexity.{{sfn|Elson|2008|p=92}}
In May 1939, Thamrin spearheaded an effort to unite eight nationalist organisations, including Parindra, in the [[Indonesian Political Federation]] ({{lang|id|Gaboengan Politiek Indonesia}}, or GAPI). The group had four main goals: Indonesian self-determination, national unity, a democratically elected party answering to the Indonesian people, and solidarity between Indonesians and the Dutch to combat fascism.{{sfn|Kahin|1952|pp=96–97}}
On 6 January 1941, Thamrin was put under [[house arrest]] under suspicion of aiding the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|advancing Japanese forces]];{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} he had previously maintained warm relations with Japanese residents of the Indies.{{sfn|Elson|2008|p=63}} Already ill, he died five days after his arrest.{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} He was buried in [[Karet Bivak Cemetery]], [[Central Jakarta]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Even after you}}
==Legacy== [[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Jalan Thamrin TMnr 20018355.jpg|thumb|[[Jalan M.H. Thamrin]] in 1993]] Thamrin has several objects named after him, including [[Jalan M.H. Thamrin]], a thoroughfare in Central Jakarta,{{sfn|JCG, Mohammad Hoesni Thamrin}} and Mohammad Husni Thamrin School for the Gifted, a school in [[East Jakarta]] for students with an [[IQ]] of more than 120.{{sfn|Sabarini 2009, Prestigious high school}} His old home on Kenari street in [[Senen]], Central Jakarta, is now a museum dedicated to his life.{{sfn|JCG, Gedung Muhammad Husni}} Two statues of Thamrin have been erected in Jakarta: a bust near the [[Monas|National Monument]] and a full-body statue in front of the Thamrin Museum.{{sfn|JCG, Husni Thamrin, Patung}}
He was declared a [[National Hero of Indonesia]] in 1964.{{sfn|Ajisaka|Damayanti|2010|p=132}}
