{{Infobox military person |name=Nikolaos Zervas |native_name=Νικόλαος Ζέρβας |native_name_lang=ell |birth_date=1800 |death_date={{death year and age|1869|1800}} |birth_place=[[Souli]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (now Greece) |death_place=[[Agrinio]], Greece |image=Nickolaos Zervas.jpg |image_size=200 |caption= |nickname= |allegiance={{flag|Greece|royal}} |branch=[[Hellenic Army]] |serviceyears=1821&ndash;1854 |rank=Major General |commands= |unit= |battles= {{plainlist| * [[Greek War of Independence]] (1821–1830) * [[Epirus Revolt of 1854]] }} |awards= |laterwork=}}
'''Nikolaos Zervas''' ({{lang-el|Νικόλαος Ζέρβας}}, 1800–1869) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] revolutionary and [[Hellenic Army|Army]] general.
Zervas was born in [[Souli]], [[Epirus]], then [[Ottoman Empire]], and became one of the leaders of the [[Souliotes]]. Zervas participated in the [[Greek War of Independence]] (1821–1830) and distinguished at the [[Battle of Analatos]] (April 1827).<ref name=Ekdotike>{{cite book | title=Παγκόσμιο Βιογραφικό Λεξικό ("Universal Biographical Lexicon") | publisher=Ekdotiki Athninon | location=Athens | volume =III |year=1990 |pages=414–415}}</ref> At March 1828, together with another revolutionary leader, Dimos Tselios, managed to push back an advancing [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] (Turkish-Albanian) force at [[Acharnes|Menidi]], [[Attica]].<ref>[[Douglas Dakin]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Rk1iVvOr6RUC&pg=PA266 The Greek struggle for independence, 1821–1833]. University of California Press, 1973 {{ISBN|978-0-520-02342-0}}, p. 266</ref>
After Independence, Zervas participated in an anti-royalist revolt in [[Acarnania]] (1836).<ref name=Ekdotike/> At 1854, already a major general in the Hellenic Army, he resigned his post and joined general [[Theodoros Grivas]] in the [[Epirus revolt of 1854]]. The revolt aimed at the union of Epirus with the [[Kingdom of Greece]], but failed.<ref>M. V. Sakellariou. [https://books.google.com/books?ei=-nSSTIeVMYWSswafoMj3CQ&ct=result&id=UV1oAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22the+regular+army+and+volunteers%2C%22%2Bepirus&q=%22where+he+was+joined+soon+afterwards+by+soldiers+of+the+regular+army+and+volunteers%2C+mostly+Souliots%2C+led+by+general+N.+Zervas%22#search_anchor Epirus, 4000 years of Greek history and civilization]. Ekdotikē Athēnōn, 1997, {{ISBN|978-960-213-371-2}}, p. 289: "where he was joined soon afterwards by soldiers of the regular army and volunteers, mostly Souliots, led by general N. Zervas".</ref>
